Anonymous Sun 25 Apr 2021 03:38:44 No.38167034 Report

>>38162434
>other than a decent dictonary, thesaurus,
I will suggest enhance this part of your collection. Go to used book stores and look for old dictionaries. Try to get one from the 1960s, 1940s, and 1920s at least. If you're lucky, you may even get one from 1900 or earlier. One of the most tragic losses in my life was an 1848 dictionary, when they printed it on only one side of a page, and it got nabbed by someone (who I could never prove did it) during one of my moves. Picked it up for $5, found out later it was worth about $300, really rare. But, whenever I look up any word, I also look them up in several dictionaries. One of my current fallbacks is a two volume from the 1920s. There is some serious and interesting changes in meaning and usage, as well as odd words that don't appear in modern dictionaries.

If you have money to invest, invest in a modern Oxford multi-volume dictionary. It has EVERYTHING in it, and will give yo clues & inspiration in numerous ways.

And, the same for thesauruses. There are several editions of the classic Roget's, and they drop & add words between them. I've got a 3rd, 4th, and 5th edition and almost always look up words in all three to find changes & differences. Sometimes they can be dramatic. There also are several different thesauruses, not just Roget's. Look for them in use book stores, and the older ones can get very interesting.

Now, get some books written by authors from the turn of the century. Mark Twain, Jack London, Jules Verne. Study their styles & grammar. Jack London used to write newspaper articles, you can search & find some ion the internet for free.

Oh, BTW, Project Gutenberg: http://www.gutenberg.org/

More books than you can read in your lifetime for free. Browse around, read, study styles from genres and time periods.

Random fun find, 1892 The Writer magazine, one volume available, the prose is astonishing:
http://www.gutenberg.org/files/26128/26128-h/26128-h.htm

Far more applicable than you might think. Sound and Sense deals mostly with delivery, not content. The structure of that is basically identical in and out of prose. Literary devices are literary devices. This is extra-true in greentext where you can also abide by any advice regarding line and stanza construction. Really, it's texture I recommend it for though. A lot of stories that get posted here suffer from long, and/or over-consistent sentence structure. How you write the words matters a lot when it comes to achieving a desired tone/ goal, often as much as what those words are. If you're writing about a character suffering extreme fear, for instance, your sentence structure will make the distinction between "dread" and "panic".
